Introduction to statistical modelling

Shane Blowes

28 January 2021

Statistical modelling

Short introduction to statistical models:

  • linear models
  • generalised linear models
  • non-linear models (e.g., basis expansion, generalised additive models, LOESS)

Linear models

Linear models take the form: \[ y_i = \beta x_i + \epsilon_i,\] where \(y_i\) is the observed response variable (here species richness), \(\beta\) is a vector of estimated (unknown) parameters, \(x_i\) are (known) covariates (can be continuous or categorical predictors), and \(\epsilon_i\) are random variables (mutually independent with zero mean and variance, \(\sigma^2\))

All statistical modelling involves a trade-off between underfitting and overfitting.

  • Underfitting results in poor prediction by learning too little from the data
  • Overfitting results in poor prediction by learning too much from the data

Generalized linear models

Extend linear models to allow for response distributions other than normal. Now, our observed values, \(Y_i\), are drawn from the a distribution of the so-called exponential family (e.g., Bernoulli, normal, gamma, exponential, Poisson, beta). The basic structure remains familiar, but with the addition of a 'link' function.

\(E(Y_i)=\mu_i\), and \(var(Y_i)=\sigma^2\)

\(g(\mu_i)=\beta X_i\), where \(g()\) is a link function.

For example, all the models above assume normally distributed error, so

\(Y_i\) ~ \(N(\mu_i, \sigma^2)\)

\(E(Y_i)=\mu_i\), and \(var(Y_i)=\sigma^2\)

\(g(\mu_i)=\beta X_i\), where \(g()\) is referred to as the identity link function.

Alternatively, as our estimate of species richness arises from a count process, we could formulate the model using the poisson distribution

\(Y_i\) ~ \(poisson(\mu_i)\)

\(E(Y_i)=\mu_i\), and \(var(Y_i)=\mu_i\)

\(log(\mu_i)=\beta X_i\), and \(g()\) is now the log link function.
